Here's a `ProductDetailViewModel` using **CommunityToolkit.Mvvm** (recommended approach — source generators handle all change notification):

```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.ComponentModel;
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Input;

public partial class ProductDetailViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _name = string.Empty;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private decimal _price;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isAvailable;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task LoadAsync()
    {
        // Simulate async fetch
        await Task.Delay(500);
        Name = "Widget Pro";
        Price = 29.99m;
        IsAvailable = true;
    }
}
```

The source generator creates public properties (`Name`, `Price`, `IsAvailable`) that raise `PropertyChanged` automatically, plus a `LoadCommand` (IAsyncRelayCommand).

**XAML with compiled bindings:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             x:DataType="vm:ProductDetailViewModel">

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="16" Spacing="12">
        <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="24" />
        <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='Price: {0:C2}'}" />
        <Label Text="{Binding IsAvailable, StringFormat='In Stock: {0}'}" />
        <Button Text="Load Product"
                Command="{Binding LoadCommand}" />
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**

- `x:DataType` at the page root enables compiled bindings (8–20× faster, AOT-safe)
- `[ObservableProperty]` eliminates boilerplate `INotifyPropertyChanged` plumbing
- `[RelayCommand]` on an async method generates `LoadCommand` with built-in `IsRunning`/`CanBeCanceled` support
- PropertyChanged is auto-marshalled to the UI thread, so setting properties from `Task.Run` is safe

**NuGet package needed:** `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm` (≥ 8.2)
